'''BlackRock, Inc.''' is an American [[Multinational corporation|multi-national]] [[investment company]] based in [[New York City]]. Founded in 1988, initially as an [[enterprise risk management]] and [[fixed income]] institutional [[asset manager]], BlackRock is the world's largest asset manager, with USD 10 trillion in [[assets under management]] as of December 31, 2022.<ref name=10K/> BlackRock operates globally with 70 offices in 30 countries, and clients in 100 countries.<ref name=10K/> BlackRock is the manager of the [[iShares]] group of [[exchange-traded fund]]s, and along with [[The Vanguard Group]] and [[State Street Corporation|State Street]], it is considered to be one of the Big Three [[index fund]] managers.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Bebchuk |first1=Lucian |author-link=Lucian Bebchuk |last2=Hirst |first2=Scott |date=2019 |title=Index Funds and the Future of Corporate Governance: Theory, Evidence, and Policy |url=https://columbialawreview.org/content/index-funds-and-the-future-of-corporate-governance-theory-evidence-and-policy/ |journal=[[Columbia Law Review]] |volume=119 |issue=8 |pages=2029–2146 |ssrn=3282794}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=McLaughlin |first1=David |last2=Massa |first2=Annie |date=January 9, 2020 |title=The Hidden Dangers of the Great Index Fund Takeover |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2020-01-09/the-hidden-dangers-of-the-great-index-fund-takeover |access-date=June 7, 2021 |website=Bloomberg Businessweek}}</ref> Its [[Aladdin (BlackRock)|Aladdin]] software keeps track of investment portfolios for many major financial institutions and its BlackRock Solutions division provides financial [[risk management]] services.<ref name="economist.com" /> BlackRock is ranked 184th on the [[Fortune 500|''Fortune'' 500]] list of the largest United States corporations by revenue.<ref>{{Cite web |title=BlackRock | url=https://fortune.com/company/blackrock/fortune500/ | work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]}}</ref>

BlackRock has sought to position itself as an industry leader in [[environmental, social, and corporate governance]] (ESG). It has been criticized by some for investing in companies that are involved in [[fossil fuels]], the [[arms industry]], and [[Human rights in China|human rights violations in China]]. Others have scrutinized BlackRock for its efforts to reduce its investments in companies that contribute to [[climate change]] and [[gun violence]] and its promotion of [[gender diversity]]; the U.S. states of West Virginia, Florida, and Louisiana have divested money away from or refuse to do business with the firm because of its ESG policies. The company has also faced criticism for its close ties with the [[Federal Reserve]] during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] and for [[anti-competitive practices]] due to its significant ownership stakes in so many companies.

==History==
===1988–1999===
BlackRock was founded in 1988 by [[Larry Fink]], [[Robert S. Kapito]], [[Susan Wagner]], Barbara Novick, Ben Golub, Hugh Frater, Ralph Schlosstein, and Keith Anderson<ref>{{Cite web |last=Appell |first=Douglas |date=2012-07-09 |title=BlackRock departures spur talk about Fink's future |url=https://www.pionline.com/article/20120709/PRINT/307099977/blackrock-departures-spur-talk-about-finks-future |access-date=2019-04-15 |website=Pensions & Investments |language=en}}</ref> to provide institutional clients with asset management services from a risk management perspective.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2013-12-05 |title=The rise of BlackRock |newspaper=The Economist |url=https://www.economist.com/leaders/2013/12/05/the-rise-of-blackrock |access-date=2019-04-15 |issn=0013-0613}}</ref> Fink, Kapito, Golub and Novick had worked together at [[First Boston]], where Fink and his team were pioneers in the [[Mortgage-backed security|mortgage-backed securities]] market in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Larry Fink Q&A: "I Don't Identify as Powerful" |newspaper=Bloomberg.com |publisher=Bloomberg |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2017-blackrock-larry-fink-interview/ |access-date=2019-04-15 }}</ref> During Fink's tenure, he had lost $90 million as head of First Boston. That experience was the motivation to develop what he and the others considered to be excellent risk management and fiduciary practices. Initially, Fink sought funding (for initial operating capital) from Pete Peterson of [[The Blackstone Group]] who believed in Fink's vision of a firm devoted to risk management. Peterson called it Blackstone Financial Management.<ref name=":4">{{Cite book |last1=Carey |first1=David |last2=Morris |first2=John E. |date=2012 |title=King of Capital: The Remarkable Rise, Fall, and Rise Again of Steve Schwarzman and Blackstone |publisher=Crown Publishing Group |isbn=9780307886026 |page=59 |language=en |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DE8jTajp7PAC&pg=PA59 }}</ref> In exchange for a 50 percent stake in the bond business, initially Blackstone gave Fink and his team a $5 million credit line. Within months, the business had turned profitable, and by 1989 the group's assets had quadrupled to $2.7 billion. The percent of the stake owned by Blackstone also fell to 40%, compared to Fink's staff.<ref name=":4" />

By 1992, Blackstone had a stake equating to about 35% of the company, and [[Stephen A. Schwarzman]] and Fink were considering selling shares to the public.<ref name=heroic/> The firm adopted the name BlackRock, and was managing $17 billion in assets by the end of the year. At the end of 1994, BlackRock was managing $53 billion.<ref name="main-history">{{Cite web |title=History |url=https://www.blackrock.com/corporate/about-us/blackrock-history |publisher=BlackRock}}</ref> In 1994, Schwarzman and Fink had an internal dispute over methods of compensation and equity.<ref name=heroic/> Fink wanted to share equity with new hires, to lure talent from [[bank]]s, unlike Schwarzman, who did not want to further lower Blackstone's stake.<ref name=heroic/> They agreed to part ways, and Schwarzman sold BlackRock, a decision he later called a "heroic mistake."<ref name=heroic>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-09-30/schwarzman-says-selling-blackrock-was-heroic-mistake | title=Schwarzman Says Selling BlackRock Was 'Heroic' Mistake | first=Devin | last=Banerjee | work=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=September 30, 2013 | url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=BlackRock is Wall Street's object of fantasy M&A |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-blackrock-blackstone-group-breakingvi/breakingviews-blackrock-is-wall-streets-object-of-fantasy-ma-idUSKBN1YR1JI |last1=Foley |first1=John | last2=Cox | first2=Rob | work=[[Reuters]] |date=December 23, 2019}}</ref> In June 1994, Blackstone sold a mortgage-securities unit with $23 billion in assets to [[PNC Financial Services]] for $240 million.<ref name="fortune-admired" /> The unit had traded mortgages and other fixed-income assets, and during the sales process the unit changed its name from Blackstone Financial Management to BlackRock Financial Management.<ref name=heroic/> Schwarzman remained with Blackstone, while Fink became chairman and CEO of BlackRock.<ref name=heroic/>

=== 1999–2009 ===
In September 1999, BlackRock became a [[public company]], selling shares a $14 each via an [[initial public offering]] on the [[New York Stock Exchange]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://money.cnn.com/1999/09/26/markets/ipos/ | title=Here come the IPOs | work=[[CNN]] | date=September 26, 1999}}</ref><ref name=main-history/> By the end of 1999, BlackRock was managing $165 billion in assets.<ref name=main-history/> BlackRock grew both organically and by acquisition.

In 2000, under the direction of [[Charles Hallac]], BlackRock launched BlackRock Solutions, its analytics and risk management division. The division grew from the [[Aladdin (BlackRock)|Aladdin System]], the enterprise investment system, Green Package, the Risk Reporting Service, PAG (portfolio analytics), and AnSer, the interactive analytics.<ref name="economist.com">[https://www.economist.com/news/briefing/21591164-getting-100-billion-assets-single-risk-management-system-huge-achievement Briefing: BlackRock - The Monolith And The Markets], ''[[The Economist]]'', December 7, 2013, pp. 24-26.</ref>

In August 2004, BlackRock made its first major acquisition, buying State Street Research & Management's holding company SSRM Holdings, Inc. from [[MetLife]] for $325 million in cash and $50 million in stock. The acquisition increased BlackRock's assets under management from $314 billion to $325 billion.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=BlackRock Acquiring State Street Research from MetLife |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20040826005225/en/BlackRock-Purchase-SSRM-Holdings-MetLife-BlackRock-Hold | publisher=[[Business Wire]] |date=August 24, 2004}}</ref> The deal included the mutual-fund business State Street Research & Management in 2005.<ref name=fortune-admired/>

BlackRock merged with [[Merrill (company)|Merrill]]'s Investment Managers division (MLIM) in 2006,<ref name=main-history/><ref>{{Cite news  |title=BlackRock and a hard place |url=https://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2006/02/16/blackrock-and-a-hard-place | newspaper=[[The Economist]]  |date=February 16, 2006}}</ref> halving PNC's ownership and giving [[Merrill (company)|Merrill]] a 49.5% stake in the company.<ref>{{Cite web |title=BlackRock, Merrill fund unit complete merger |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/merrill-lynch-investment-managers-blackrock-close-merger | last=Spence |first=John |website=[[MarketWatch]] | date=October 2, 2006 | url-access=limited}}</ref>

In October 2007, BlackRock acquired the fund-of-funds business of Quellos Capital Management.<ref name="quellos">{{Cite news | url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/19430953 | title=BlackRock to Buy Quellos Fund of Funds Business | agency=[[Reuters]] | work=[[CNBC]] | date=June 26, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=DeSilver |first=Drew|title=Quellos is selling unit to BlackRock in $1.72 billion deal |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/quellos-is-selling-unit-to-blackrock-in-172-billion-deal/ | work=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=June 27, 2007}}</ref>

BlackRock Solutions was retained by the [[U. S. Treasury Department]] in May 2009<ref name=bb-power/> to analyze, unwind, and price the [[toxic asset]]s that were owned by [[Bear Stearns]], [[American International Group]], [[Freddie Mac]], [[Morgan Stanley]], and other financial firms that were affected in the [[2007–2008 financial crisis]].<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Rappaport |first1=Liz |last2=Craig |first2=Susanne |title=BlackRock Wears Multiple Hats |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124269131342732625 |date=May 19, 2009 |issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref name="vfair-job">Andrews, Suzanna. [http://www.vanityfair.com/business/features/2010/04/fink-201004 Larry Fink's $12 Trillion Shadow], ''Vanity Fair'', April 2010: "There is little doubt among the financial establishment in Washington and on Wall Street that BlackRock was the best choice to handle the government's problems."</ref> The [[Federal Reserve]] allowed BlackRock to superintend the $130 billion-debt settlement of [[Bear Stearns]] and [[American International Group]].<ref name="Wash_Post" />

In 2009, BlackRock became the largest asset manager worldwide.<ref name=fortune-admired/>

In April 2009, BlackRock acquired R3 Capital Management, LLC and management of its $1.5 billion fund.<ref>{{Cite news | title=BlackRock to Acquire R3 Capital |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2009/04/17/blackrock-to-acquire-r3-capital/ |date=April 17, 2009}}</ref>

===2010–2019===
In February 2010, to raise capital needed during the financial crisis, [[Barclays]] sold its Global Investors unit (BGI), which included its exchange traded fund business, [[iShares]], to BlackRock for US$13.5 billion and Barclays acquired a near-20% stake in BlackRock.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.investmentnews.com/blackrock-wraps-up-merger-with-barclays-global-investors-25639 | title=BlackRock wraps up merger with Barclays Global Investors | agency=[[Associated Press]] | date=February 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | title=US giant BlackRock buys arm of Barclays bank |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2009/jun/12/blackrock-to-buy-barclays-bank-arm |date=12 June 2009}}</ref>

On April 1, 2011, BlackRock was added as a component of the [[S&P 500]] [[stock market index]].<ref name="bweek-replace">{{Cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/blackrock-sp500/update-1-blackrock-to-join-sp-500-index-idUSN2929979120110329 | title=BlackRock to join S&P 500 index | work=[[Reuters]] | date=March 29, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=http://archive.boston.com/business/healthcare/articles/2011/03/29/blackrock_to_join_sp_500_index_replacing_genzyme/ | title=BlackRock to join S&P 500 index, replacing Genzyme | work=[[The Boston Globe]] | date=March 29, 2011}}</ref>

In 2013, ''Fortune'' listed BlackRock on its annual list of the world's 50 Most Admired Companies.<ref name="fortune-admired">{{Cite news |title=BlackRock: The $4.3 trillion force |work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |url=https://fortune.com/2014/07/07/blackrock-larry-fink/ | first=CAROL J. | last=LOOMIS | date=July 7, 2014}}</ref>

In 2014, BlackRock's $4 trillion under management made it the "world's biggest asset manager".<ref name=econ-br>{{Cite news |title=Shadow and substance |newspaper=[[The Economist]] |url=https://www.economist.com/news/special-report/21601621-banks-retreat-wake-financial-crisis-shadow-banks-are-taking-growing |date=May 10, 2014}}</ref>

At the end of 2014, the [[Sovereign Wealth Fund Institute]] reported that 65% of Blackrock's assets under management were made up of [[institutional investor]]s.<ref name="swf-institute">{{Cite web |date=n.d. |title=Is BlackRock Too Big |url=https://www.swfinstitute.org/news/26040/is-blackrock-too-big |access-date=9 February 2015 |website=Sovereign Wealth Fund Institute}}</ref>

By June 30, 2015, BlackRock had US$4.721 trillion of assets under management.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2016-07-14 |title=BlackRock profit falls as shift from stocks hits fee revenue |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-blackrock-results-idUSKCN0ZU13V |access-date=2019-01-15}}</ref> On August 26, 2015, BlackRock entered into a definitive agreement to acquire [[Future Advisor]],<ref name="future-advisor">{{Cite web |title=BlackRock to Acquire Future Advisor |url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=119943&p=irol-news Articled=2082123 |access-date=26 August 2015 |website=BlackRock Press Releases |publisher=BlackRock}}</ref> a digital wealth management provider with reported assets under management of $600 million.<ref name="future-tech">{{Cite web |last=Tepper |first=Fitz |date=24 June 2015 |title=YC Alum Future Advisor Is Now Managing $600 Million In Assets |url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/06/24/yc-alum-futureadvisor-is-now-managing-600-million/ |access-date=12 September 2015 |publisher=TechCrunch}}</ref> Under the deal, Future Advisor would operate as a business within BlackRock Solutions (BRS).<ref name=future-advisor/> BlackRock announced in November 2015 that they would wind down the BlackRock Global Ascent hedge fund after losses. The Global Ascent fund had been its only dedicated global macro fund, as BlackRock was "better known for its mutual funds and exchange traded funds." At the time, BlackRock managed $51 billion in hedge funds, with $20 billion of that in funds of hedge funds.<ref name="fund-losses">{{Cite news |last=Stevenson |first=Alexandra |date=2015-11-18 |title=BlackRock to Wind Down Macro Hedge Fund |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/19/business/dealbook/blackrock-to-wind-down-macro-hedge-fund.html |access-date=2015-11-19 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

In March 2017, BlackRock, after a six-month review led by [[Mark Wiseman]], initiated a restructuring of its $8bn actively-managed fund business, resulting in the departure of seven portfolio managers and a $25m charge in Q2, replacing certain funds with quantitative investment strategies.<ref name="ft-cuts">{{Cite news |date=27 March 2017 |title=BlackRock cuts ranks of stock picking fund managers |work=[[Financial Times]] |url=https://www.ft.com/content/b0056320-13e3-11e7-b0c1-37e417ee6c76 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/BVkup |archive-date=2022-12-11 |url-status=live |access-date=30 March 2017|url-access=subscription}}</ref>

By April 2017, [[iShares]] business accounted for $1.41tn, or 26 percent, of BlackRock's total assets under management, and 37 percent of BlackRock's base fee income.<ref name="ft-record">{{Cite news |last=Foley |first=Stephen |date=April 19, 2017 |title=BlackRock assets under management hit $5.4tn on record ETF inflows |work=[[Financial Times]] |url=https://www.ft.com/content/adeae206-2502-11e7-8691-d5f7e0cd0a16 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/6YUDT |archive-date=2022-12-11 |url-status=live |access-date=May 10, 2017|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In April 2017, BlackRock backed the inclusion of mainland Chinese shares in MSCI's global index for the first time.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hughes |first=Jennifer |title=BlackRock backs mainland China shares for MSCI benchmarks |work=[[Financial Times]] |date=April 20, 2017 |url=https://www.ft.com/content/6f0943e6-257c-11e7-8691-d5f7e0cd0a16 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/1PiMS |archive-date=2022-12-11 |url-status=live |url-access=subscription}}</ref>

===2020–present===
In March 2020, the [[Federal Reserve]] chose BlackRock to manage two corporate bond-buying programs in response to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], the $500 billion Primary Market Corporate Credit Facility (PMCCF) and the Secondary Market Corporate Credit Facility (SMCCF), as well as purchase by the [[Federal Reserve]] of commercial mortgage-backed securities (CMBS) guaranteed by [[Government National Mortgage Association]], [[Fannie Mae]], or [[Freddie Mac]].<ref name="Wash_Post">Annie Massa. [https://web.archive.org/web/20200618233642/https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/why-blackrock-has-a-role-in-the-fed-bond-buying-spree/2020/05/21/853f461c-9b74-11ea-ad79-eef7cd734641_story.html?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=referral&utm_campaign=wp_business Why BlackRock Has a Role in the Fed Bond-Buying Spree], ''The Washington Post'', May 22, 2020</ref><ref>Sophie Baker. [https://www.pionline.com/markets/fed-chooses-blackrock-pandemic-support-programs Fed chooses BlackRock for pandemic support programs], ''Pensions & Investments'', March 25, 2020</ref><ref>Jonnelle Marte. [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-fed-primarycredit/fed-opens-primary-market-corporate-bond-facility-idUSKBN2402J6 Fed opens primary market corporate bond facility], ''Reuters'', June 29, 2020</ref>

In August 2020, BlackRock received approval from the [[China Securities Regulatory Commission]] to set up a mutual fund business in the country. This made BlackRock the first global asset manager to get consent from the Chinese government to start operations in the country.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Zacks Equity Research |title=BlackRock Gets Nod to Set Up Mutual Fund Business in China (Revised) |url=https://www.nasdaq.com/articles/blackrock-gets-nod-to-set-up-mutual-fund-business-in-china-revised-2020-09-02 | work=[[Nasdaq]] | date=September 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=BlackRock Gets Nod to Set Up Mutual Fund Business in China (Revised) |url=https://news.yahoo.com/blackrock-gets-nod-set-mutual-135001227.html |access-date=2020-09-16 |website=news.yahoo.com |language=en-US}}</ref>

In January 2020, [[PNC Financial Services]] sold its stake in BlackRock for $14.4 billion.<ref>{{cite news |last=SABATINI |first=PATRICIA |title=PNC sold its shares to Blackrock stake for $14.4 billion |work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|url=https://www.post-gazette.com/business/pittsburgh-company-news/2020/05/15/PNC-sells-Blackrock-stake-for-14-4-billion/stories/202005150123 |date=May 15, 2020}}</ref>

In November 2021, Blackrock lowered its investment in [[India]] while increasing investment in [[China]]. The firm maintains a dedicated India Fund, through which it invests in Indian start-ups [[Byju's]], [[Paytm]], and [[Pine Labs]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2021-11-23 |title=World's biggest asset manager BlackRock trimming investments in India, more optimistic on China |url=https://theprint.in/economy/worlds-biggest-asset-manager-blackrock-trimming-investments-in-india-more-optimistic-on-china/770519/ |access-date=2022-03-24 |website=ThePrint |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=BlackRock says it's time to buy China stocks and trim India exposure: Report |url=https://www.businesstoday.in/markets/stocks/story/blackrock-says-its-time-to-buy-china-stocks-and-trim-india-exposure-report-313143-2021-11-23 |access-date=2022-03-24 |website=Business Today |date=23 November 2021 |language=en}}</ref>

In April 2023, the company was hired to sell $114 billion in assets of [[Signature Bank]] and [[Silicon Valley Bank]] after the [[2023 global banking crisis]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-04-05/blackrock-hired-to-sell-114-billion-in-failed-banks-securities | title=BlackRock to Sell $114 Billion of Failed Banks' Securities | first1=Dan | last1=Reichl | first2=Silla | last2=Brush | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=April 5, 2023 | url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.ft.com/content/0db00ba2-6603-4d09-b736-60a0307bc75b | title=BlackRock to manage $114bn of asset disposals after US bank failures | first1=Jennifer | last1=Hughes | first2=Brooke | last2=Masters | work=[[Financial Times]] | date=April 5, 2023}}</ref>

==Finances==
In 2020, the non-profit [[American Economic Liberties Project]] issued a report highlighting the fact that "the 'Big Three' asset management firms—BlackRock, [[Vanguard Group|Vanguard]] and [[State Street Corporation|State Street]]—manage over $15 trillion in combined global assets under management, an amount equivalent to more than three-quarters of U.S. gross domestic product."<ref>[https://www.economicliberties.us/our-work/new-money-trust/#_edn13 The New Money Trust: How Large Money Managers Control Our Economy and What We Can Do About It], November 23, 2020</ref> The report called for structural reforms and better regulation of the financial markets. In 2021, BlackRock managed over $10 trillion in assets under management, about 40% of the GDP of the United States (nominal $25.347 trillion in 2022)<ref name="GDP IMF">{{cite web |url=https://www.imf.org/en/Publications/WEO/weo-database/2022/April|title=World Economic Outlook Database, April 2022 |date=April 2022 |website=IMF.org |publisher=[[International Monetary Fund]]|access-date=April 19, 2022}}</ref>

