==Criticism==
===Influence and power===
In 2010, Ralph Schlosstein, the CEO of [[Evercore Partners]] and a BlackRock founder, called BlackRock "the most influential financial institution in the world."<ref name="bb-power">{{Cite web |last=Kolhatkar |first=Sheelah |title=Fink Builds BlackRock Powerhouse Without Goldman Sachs Backlash |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-09/larry-fink-builds-blackrock-into-powerhouse-without-goldman-sachs-backlash.html | work=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=December 9, 2010}}</ref>

Due to its power and the sheer size and scope of its financial assets and activities, BlackRock has been called the world's largest [[Shadow banking system|shadow bank]].<ref name=bazonline-br>{{Cite news |title=Die grösste Schattenbank der Welt |work=[[Basler Zeitung]] |url=http://bazonline.ch/wirtschaft/unternehmen-und-konjunktur/Die-groesste-Schattenbank-der-Welt/story/27331110 |date=November 20, 2012}}</ref><ref name=econ-br/> In 2020, U.S. Representatives [[Katie Porter]] and [[Jesús "Chuy" García]] proposed a U.S. House bill aiming to restrain BlackRock and other so-called shadow banks.<ref name=vampire/> On March 4, 2021, U.S. Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]] suggested that BlackRock should be designated "[[too big to fail]]", and should be regulated accordingly.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cox |first=Jeff |title=Yellen supports banks' share buybacks. Sen. Warren wants BlackRock designated too big to fail |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/03/24/yellen-supports-buybacks-warren-wants-blackrock-deemed-too-big-to-fail.html |website=[[CNBC]] |date=March 24, 2021}}</ref>

BlackRock invests the funds of its clients (for example, the owners of [[iShares]] [[exchange-traded fund]] units) in numerous publicly traded companies, some of which compete with each other.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Fichtner |first1=Jan |last2=Heemskerk |first2=Eelke M. |last3=Garcia-Bernardo |first3=Javier |date=2017 |title=Hidden power of the Big Three? Passive index funds, re-concentration of corporate ownership, and new financial risk |journal=Business and Politics |volume=19 |issue=2 |pages=298–326 |doi=10.1017/bap.2017.6 |doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=Nov 3, 2016 |title=Who owns big business: the rise of passive investors (@uvaCORPNET) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OYpCxXuF3M8 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211221/OYpCxXuF3M8 |archive-date=2021-12-21 |url-status=live|website=YouTube}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=May 10, 2018 |title=BlackRock - The company that owns the world? (Investigate Europe) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A4foal20UTA | archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211221/A4foal20UTA |archive-date=2021-12-21 |url-status=live|website=YouTube}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Because of the size of BlackRock's funds, the company is among the top shareholders of many companies, including the largest companies in the world. BlackRock states these shares are ultimately owned by the company's clients, not by BlackRock itself – a view shared by multiple independent academics – but acknowledges it can exercise shareholder votes on behalf of these clients, in many cases without client input.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-business-investment-idUSL2N2WI1K4 |title=Fact Check-Video claiming BlackRock and Vanguard 'own all the biggest corporations in the world' is missing context |work=[[Reuters]] |date=April 20, 2022}}</ref>

This concentration of ownership has raised concerns of possible [[anti-competitive practices]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Solomon |first=Steven |title=Rise of Institutional Investors Raises Questions of Collusion |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/13/business/dealbook/rise-of-institutional-investors-raisesquestions-of-collusion.html |website=New York Times|date=April 12, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Guest |first=Greta |title=Common ownership of big banks kills competition |url=https://news.umich.edu/common-ownership-of-big-banks-kills-competition/ |website=University of Michigan News|date=February 1, 2016}}</ref> A 2014 study analyzed the effects of this type of common ownership on airline ticket prices.<ref>{{Cite journal |date=2014 |title=Anticompetitive Effects of Common Ownership |journal=Journal of Finance |volume=73 |pages=1513–1565 |doi=10.2139/ssrn.2427345 |s2cid=18018480}}</ref> The study found that "Prices go up and quantity goes down when the airlines competing on a given route are more commonly owned by the same set of investors." The authors noted that this price increase does not necessarily imply conscious collusion among the common owners, but could perhaps be that these firms are now "too lazy to compete" with themselves.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kosdrosky |first=Terry |title=Competitors With Common Owners |url=https://michiganross.umich.edu/alumni/dividend/fall2015/competitors-common-owners |website=University of Michigan |date=September 17, 2015 }}</ref>

BlackRock has been the subject of [[conspiracy theories]], including the conspiracy theory that BlackRock owns both [[Fox News]] and [[Dominion Voting Systems]], which [[Snopes]] described as "false" and [[PolitiFact]] described as "mostly false".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/does-blackrock-own-fox-news-dominion-voting/ |title=Does BlackRock Own Both Fox News and Dominion Voting Systems? |date=27 April 2023 |publisher=[[Snopes]] |accessdate=2023-04-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2023/apr/26/facebook-posts/blackrock-fox-and-tucker-carlson-untangling-a-web/ |title=Facebook posts |accessdate=2023-04-27}}</ref> Some BlackRock conspiracy theories have also incorporated [[antisemitic conspiracy theories|antisemitism]], such as the conspiracy theory that Jewish people including BlackRock founder Robert Kapito are part of a [[cabal]] responsible for [[COVID-19 misinformation|COVID]] and a "COVID agenda".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/diaspora/antisemitism/article-712270 |title='COVID agenda is Jewish': Antisemitic flyer found at Melbourne synagogue |publisher=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |accessdate=2023-04-27}}</ref>

====Cross ownership====
BlackRock is a shareholder in many institutional investors that own shares in BlackRock. This chain of ownership is similar to [[cross ownership]] structures which have been identified in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 6, 2019 |title=Getting the UK's House in order |url=https://www.globalwitness.org/en/campaigns/corruption-and-money-laundering/anonymous-company-owners/getting-uks-house-order/ |website=Global Witness}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Knobel |first=Andres |date=September 6, 2019 |title=More beneficial ownership loopholes to plug: circular ownership, fragmented control and companies as parties to the trust |url=https://www.taxjustice.net/2019/09/06/more-beneficial-ownership-loopholes-to-plug-circular-ownership-control-with-little-ownership-and-companies-as-parties-to-the-trust/ |website=Tax Justice Network}}</ref>

===Environmental, social and corporate governance investing===
{{main|Environmental, social and corporate governance}}

In 2017, BlackRock expanded its presence in sustainable investing and [[environmental, social and corporate governance]] (ESG) with new staff and products both in the USA and Europe with the aim to lead the evolution of the financial sector in this regard.<ref>{{Cite news |date=October 22, 2018 |title=BlackRock stakes claim on 'sustainable investing' revolution |work=[[Financial Times]] |url=https://www.ft.com/content/f66b2a9e-d53d-11e8-a854-33d6f82e62f8 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/es3AZ |archive-date=2022-12-11 |url-status=live |quote=BlackRock intends to become a global leader in “sustainable investing”, says Larry Fink, as the world's largest asset manager launched |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Chasan |first=Emily |date=2017-10-10 |title=BlackRock Names Former Obama Aide to Run Sustainable Investing |work=Bloomberg |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-10/blackrock-names-former-obama-aide-to-run-sustainable-investing}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Jarsh |first1=Melissa |last2=Chasan |first2=Emily |date=2018-06-13 |title=BlackRock, Wells Fargo Are Betting on Ethical Investing Funds for 401(k)s |work=Bloomberg |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-13/blackrock-wells-fargo-are-said-to-push-esg-funds-for-401-k-s}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Camilla Giannoni |date=October 19, 2018 |title=BlackRock hires new Switzerland CEO |url=https://citywire.ch/news/blackrock-hires-new-switzerland-ceo/a1167087 |quote=deepen our commitment to clients in Switzerland and broaden our sustainable investing footprint in Europe}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Independent Capital's Staub-Bisang to run BlackRock Switzerland | first=Angelika | last=Gruber | work=[[Reuters]] | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/blackrock-swiss/moves-independent-capitals-staub-bisang-to-run-blackrock-switzerland-idUSL8N1WZ49G |date=October 19, 2018}}</ref>

BlackRock started drawing attention to environmental and diversity issues by means of official letters to CEOs and shareholder votes together with [[activist investor]]s or investor networks such as the [[Carbon Disclosure Project]], which in 2017 backed a successful shareholder resolution for [[ExxonMobil]] to act on [[climate change]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Tarek Soliman |title=The new normal: Exxon shareholders vote in favour of climate action |url=https://www.cdp.net/en/articles/investor/the-new-normal-exxon-shareholders-vote-in-favour-of-climate-action |date=2017-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Gary McWilliams |date=2017-05-31 |title=Exxon shareholders approve climate impact report in win for activists |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-exxonmobil-climate-idUSKBN18R0DC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | first=Andrew | last=Winston |title=Does Wall Street Finally Care About Sustainability? |url=https://hbr.org/2018/01/does-wall-street-finally-care-about-sustainability |journal=[[Harvard Business Review]] |date=2018-01-19 }}</ref>

In 2018, it asked [[Russell 1000]] companies to improve [[gender diversity]] on their [[board of directors]] if they had fewer than two women on them.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Chasan |first=Emily |date=2018-11-03 |title=BlackRock Is Sick of Excuses for Corporate Boards Lacking Women |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-11-03/blackrock-is-sick-of-excuses-for-corporate-boards-lacking-women |website=Bloomberg}}</ref>

In August 2021, a former BlackRock executive who had served as the company's first global chief investment officer for sustainable investing, said he thought the firm's ESG investing was a "dangerous placebo that harms the public interest." The former executive said that financial institutions are motivated to engage in ESG investing because ESG products have higher fees, which in turn increase company profits.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Amaro |first1=Silvia |title=Blackrock's former sustainable investing chief now thinks ESG is a 'dangerous placebo' |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/08/24/blackrocks-former-sustainable-investing-chief-says-esg-is-a-dangerous-placebo.html |access-date=26 October 2021 |work=CNBC |date=24 August 2021 |language=en}}</ref>

In October 2021, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' editorial board wrote that BlackRock was pushing the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] to adopt rules requiring private companies to publicly disclose their climate impact, the diversity of their boards of directors, and other metrics. The editorial board opined that "ESG mandates, which also carry substantial litigation and reputation risks, will cause many companies to shun public markets. This would hurt stock exchanges and asset managers, but most of all retail investors."<ref>{{cite news |title=Opinion: BlackRock's Wish Is Your Command |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/follow-larry-finks-orders-or-else-blackrock-nasdaq-adena-friedman-esg-sec-11633112228 |author=The Editorial Board |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=October 24, 2021 | url-access=subscription}}</ref>

In January 2022, BlackRock founder and CEO Larry Fink defended the company's focus on ESG investing, pushing back "against accusations the asset manager was using its heft and influence to support a politically correct or progressive agenda."<ref name=cnbc>{{cite news |last1=Meredith |first1=Sam |title=BlackRock CEO Larry Fink says stakeholder capitalism is not 'woke' |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/01/18/blackrock-ceo-larry-fink-says-stakeholder-capitalism-is-not-woke.html |work=CNBC |date=January 18, 2022}}</ref> Fink said the practice of ESG "is not [[woke]]."<ref>{{cite news |title=BlackRock CEO Says Stakeholder Capitalism Isn't 'Woke'|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-01-18/blackrock-ceo-says-nothing-woke-about-stakeholder-capitalism |last1=Brush |first1=Silla |last2=Ward |first2=Russell | work=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=January 17, 2022 | url-access=limited}}</ref> 

BlackRock's emphasis on ESG has drawn criticism as "either bowing to anti-business interests" or being "merely marketing".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/01/18/business/dealbook/fink-blackrock-woke.html |last1=Sorkin |first1=Andrew Ross | authorlink1=Andrew Ross Sorkin |last2=Karaian |first2=Jason |last3=Kessler |first3=Sarah |last4=Gandel | first4=Stephen |last5=Merced |first5=Michael J. de la |last6=Hirsch |first6=Lauren |last7=Livni |first7=Ephrat | title=Larry Fink Defends Stakeholder Capitalism |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=18 January 2022}}</ref>

===Investments in contributors to climate change===
As of December 2018, BlackRock was the world's largest investor in [[coal-fired power station]]s, holding shares worth $11 billion in 56 companies in the industry.<ref>{{Cite web |title=New Research Reveals the Banks and Investors Financing the Expansion of the Global Coal Plant Fleet |url=https://urgewald.org/medien/new-research-reveals-banks-and-investors-financing-expansion-global-coal-plant-fleet | work=[[Urgewald]] |date=December 5, 2018}}</ref> BlackRock owned more oil, gas, and thermal coal reserves than any other investment management company with total reserves amounting to 9.5 gigatonnes of {{CO2}} emissions or 30 percent of total energy-related emissions from 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |title=New report confirms BlackRock's big fossil fuel problem |url=https://foe.org/news/new-report-confirms-blackrocks-big-fossil-fuel-problem/ | work=[[Friends of the Earth]] |date=December 10, 2018}}</ref> Environmental groups including the [[Sierra Club]]<ref>{{Cite news |title=New Campaign Is Calling Out BlackRock's Big Climate Problem |url=https://www.sierraclub.org/compass/2018/10/new-campaign-calling-out-blackrock-s-big-climate-problem |website=[[Sierra Club]] |date=October 5, 2018}}</ref> and [[Amazon Watch]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=BlackRock Targeted as Largest Driver of Climate Destruction in New Campaign |url=https://amazonwatch.org/news/2018/0926-blackrock-targeted-as-largest-driver-of-climate-destruction-in-new-campaign |website=[[Amazon Watch]] |date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> launched a campaign in September 2018 called "BlackRock's Big Problem",<ref name=":3">{{Cite web |title=BlackRock's Big Problem- Making the climate crisis worse |url=https://www.blackrocksbigproblem.com/ |website=BlackRock's Big Problem }}</ref> claiming that BlackRock is the "biggest driver of climate destruction on the planet", due in part to its opposition to [[fossil fuel divestment]].<ref name=":3" /> On January 10, 2020, a group of climate activists rushed inside the Paris offices of BlackRock France, painting walls and floors with warnings and accusations on the responsibility of the company in the [[effects of global warming]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=BlackRock's Paris Office Barricaded by Climate Activists |website=[[Bloomberg News]] |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-10/blackrock-s-paris-office-barricaded-by-climate-activists | first=Gaspard | last=Sebag |date=February 10, 2020 | url-access=limited}}</ref>

In May 2019, BlackRock was criticized for the environmental impact of its holdings as it was a major shareholder in every oil [[supermajors|supermajor]] except [[Total S.A.]] and in 7 of the 10 biggest coal producers.<ref>{{Cite news |title=World's biggest investor accused of dragging feet on climate crisis |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/may/21/blackrock-investor-climate-crisis-blackrock-assets |date=May 21, 2019}}</ref>

On January 14, 2020, the company shifted its investment policy; BlackRock CEO [[Larry Fink]] said that environmental [[sustainability]] would be a key goal for investment decisions.<ref name=":5">{{Cite news |last=Sorkin |first=Andrew Ross | authorlink=Andrew Ross Sorkin |title=BlackRock C.E.O. Larry Fink: Climate Crisis Will Reshape Finance |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/14/business/dealbook/larry-fink-blackrock-climate-change.html |date=2020-01-14|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> BlackRock announced that it would sell $500 million worth of coal-related assets, and created funds that would not invest in companies profiting from [[fossil fuels]].<ref name=":6">{{Cite web |title=BlackRock to sell $500 million in coal investments in climate change push |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/blackrock-puts-climate-change-first-in-its-its-investment-strategy/ | first=STEPHEN | last=GANDEL | website=[[CBS News]] | date=January 14, 2020}}</ref><ref name=":5" /> Nonetheless, BlackRock's support for shareholder resolutions requesting [[climate risk]] disclosure fell from 25% in 2019 to 14% in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cook |first=Jackie|title=How Big Fund Families Voted on Climate Change: 2020 Edition |url=https://www.morningstar.com/articles/1002749/how-big-fund-families-voted-on-climate-change-2020-edition |work=[[Morningstar, Inc.]] |date=September 28, 2020}}</ref> 

BlackRock has also been criticized regarding [[climate change]] inaction and [[deforestation]] in the [[Amazon rainforest]].<ref>{{Cite news | first=Stephen | last=Gandel | url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/amazon-fires-blackrock-investment-firm-financial-role-cbsn-originals-documentary/ | title=Investment giant BlackRock faces critics on climate change, Amazon deforestation | work=[[CBS News]] | date= March 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | first=Patrick | last=Greenfield | url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/oct/12/top-three-asset-managers-fossil-fuel-investments | title=World's Top Three Asset Managers Oversee $300bn Fossil Fuel Investments | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=October 12, 2019}}</ref> According to ''[[The New Republic]]'', BlackRock "has positioned itself as the good guy on Wall Street, and its executives as a crew of mild-mannered money managers who understand the risks of the climate crisis and the importance of diversity. But those commitments, critics say, only extend so far into the firm's day-to-day operations."<ref name=vampire>{{cite magazine |last=Aronoff |first=Kate |title=Is BlackRock the New Vampire Squid? |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/158263/blackrock-climate-change-fossil-fuel-investments |magazine=[[The New Republic]] |date=June 26, 2020}}</ref>

===Investments in gun manufacturers and the arms industry===
The [[anti-war movement]] has criticized BlackRock because BlackRock facilitates investments in the [[arms industry]] through its iShares U.S. Aerospace and Defense [[exchange-traded fund]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Gjording |first=Lindsey Rae |title=Larry Fink calls on CEOs to realize their companies' social responsibility |url=https://www.dw.com/en/larry-fink-calls-on-ceos-to-realize-their-companies-social-responsibility/a-42279452 | work=[[Deutsche Welle]] |date=January 23, 2018}}</ref> In May 2018, anti-war organizations held a demonstration outside the company's [[annual general meeting]] in Manhattan.<ref>{{Cite news | first1=Chelsia Rose | last1=Marcius | first2=Rich | last2=Schapiro |title=Anti-gun protesters rally outside BlackRock shareholder meeting to condemn its Sturm Ruger investments | url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/anti-gun-protesters-rally-blackrock-shareholder-meeting-article-1.4005409 | work=[[New York Daily News]] |date=May 23, 2018}}</ref>

After discussions with firearms manufacturers and distributors, on April 5, 2018, BlackRock introduced two new [[exchange-traded fund]]s (ETFs) that exclude stocks of gun makers and large gun retailers such as [[Walmart]], [[Dick's Sporting Goods]], [[Kroger]], [[Sturm Ruger]], [[American Outdoor Brands]], and [[Vista Outdoor]], and removed the stocks from seven existing ESG funds.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Moyer |first=Liz |title=BlackRock to offer new funds that exclude stocks of gun makers and retailers including Walmart | work=[[CNBC]] |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/05/blackrock-to-offer-new-funds-that-exclude-stocks-of-gun-makers-and-retailers-including-walmart.html |date=April 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Gibson |first=Kate |title=BlackRock unveils line of gun-free investment products | work=[[CBS News]] |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/blackrock-unveils-line-of-gun-free-investment-products/ |date=April 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Siegel |first=Rachel |title=BlackRock unveils gun-free investment options |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/business/wp/2018/04/06/blackrock-unveils-gun-free-investment-options/ |date=April 6, 2018}}</ref>

===BlackRock study on integrating ESG into banking rules===
The [[European Ombudsman]] opened an inquiry in May 2020 to inspect the commission's file on the [[European Commission]]'s decision to award a contract to BlackRock to carry out a study on integrating environmental, social and governance risks and objectives into EU banking rules ('the prudential framework'). [[European Parliament]] members questioned the impartiality of BlackRock given its investments in the sector.<ref>{{Cite web | title=European Ombudsman | url=https://www.ombudsman.europa.eu/fr/case/en/57060 | work=[[Europa (web portal)|Europa]] | date=November 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=The Commission's decision to award a contract to BlackRock to oversee the development of ESG factors in the EU banking sector and corporate investment policies |url=https://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/P-9-2020-002369_EN.html | work=[[Europa (web portal)|Europa]] | date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>

===U.S states refusing to do business with BlackRock due to ESG policies===
[[Riley Moore]], the [[State treasurer]] of West Virginia, said in June 2022 that BlackRock and five other financial institutions would no longer be allowed to do business with the state of West Virginia, because of the company's advocacy against the fossil fuel industry.<ref>{{cite news |title=West Virginia threatens to bar big banks, BlackRock over perceived fossil fuel boycotts |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/finance/west-virginia-threatens-bar-big-banks-blackrock-over-perceived-fossil-fuel-2022-06-14/ |last=Schroeder |first=Pete | work=[[Reuters]] |date=June 14, 2022}}</ref>

In December 2022, [[Jimmy Patronis]], the [[Chief Financial Officer of Florida]], announced that the [[government of Florida]] would be divesting $2 billion worth of investments under management by BlackRock, due to the firm's move to strengthen ESG standards and ESG policies.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Florida pulls $2B worth of investments from BlackRock over ESG investment after DeSantis resolution |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/3759466-florida-pulls-2b-worth-of-investments-from-blackrock-over-esg-investment-after-desantis-resolution/ |last=Folmar |first=Chloe | work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=December 2, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Florida to pull $2bn from BlackRock in spreading ESG backlash |work=[[Financial Times]] |url=https://www.ft.com/content/38f87ec9-41c6-441d-a6c2-314ff0435166 |date=December 1, 2022 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/L9xdj |archive-date=2022-12-11 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live}}</ref> BlackRock later responded to the announcement with a statement stating that the divestment would place politics over investor interest.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/business/finance/florida-pulls-2-bln-blackrock-largest-anti-esg-divestment-2022-12-01/ | title=Florida pulls $2 bln from BlackRock in largest anti-ESG divestment | work=[[Reuters]] |last=Kerber | first=Ross | date=December 1, 2022}}</ref>

In October 2022, Louisiana removed $794 million from BlackRock due to the company's support of ESG and green energy.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/business/sustainable-business/louisiana-remove-794-mln-blackrock-funds-over-esg-drive-2022-10-05/ | title=Louisiana to remove $794 mln from BlackRock funds over ESG drive | first1=Niket | last1=Nishant | first2=Mehr | last2=Bedi | work=[[Reuters]] | date=October 5, 2022}}</ref>

===Criticism of investments in China===
In August 2021, BlackRock set up its first mutual fund in China after raising over one billion dollars from 111,000 Chinese investors. BlackRock became the first foreign-owned company allowed by the Chinese government to operate a wholly-owned business in China's mutual fund industry.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chandler |first1=Clay |last2=Gordon |first2=Nicholas |title=BlackRock is 'blundering' in China—all the way to the bank |url=https://fortune.com/2021/09/09/blackrock-china-mutual-fund-investment-soros-mistake/ |access-date=25 October 2021 |work=Fortune |date=September 9, 2021 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Madhok |first1=Diksha |title=Chinese investors pour $1 billion into BlackRock's new fund |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/09/08/investing/blackrock-china-fund-intl-hnk/index.html |access-date=25 October 2021 |work=CNN |date=September 8, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=BlackRock's China unit raises $1 bln in maiden mutual fund |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/blackrocks-china-unit-raises-1-bln-maiden-mutual-fund-2021-09-08/ |work=Reuters |date=8 September 2021 |language=en}}</ref> Writing in ''The Wall Street Journal'', [[George Soros]] described BlackRock's initiative in China as a "tragic mistake" that would "damage the national security interests of the U.S. and other democracies."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Meredith |first1=Sam |title=BlackRock responds to George Soros' criticism over China investments |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/09/08/blackrock-responds-to-george-soros-criticism-over-china-investments.html |access-date=25 October 2021 |work=CNBC |date=8 September 2021 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Soros |first=George |title=Opinion: BlackRock's China Blunder |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/blackrock-larry-fink-china-hkex-sse-authoritarianism-xi-jinping-term-limits-human-rights-ant-didi-global-national-security-11630938728 |date=September 6, 2021 |issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Meredith |first=Sam |title=BlackRock responds to George Soros' criticism over China investments |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/09/08/blackrock-responds-to-george-soros-criticism-over-china-investments.html |website=[[CNBC]] |date=September 8, 2021}}</ref>

In October 2021, non-profit group [[Consumers' Research]] launched an ad campaign criticizing BlackRock's relationship with the Chinese government.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rapoza|first=Kenneth|date=October 27, 2021|title=BlackRock's China Relationship Target In Nationwide Ad Campaign|work=[[Forbes]]|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kenrapoza/2021/10/27/blackrocks-china-relationship-target-in-nationwide-ad-campaign/|access-date=October 27, 2021}}</ref>

In December 2021, it was reported that BlackRock was an investor in two companies that had been blacklisted by the US government accusing China of [[Uyghurs#Human rights abuses against Uyghurs in Xinjiang|human rights abuses]] against the [[Uyghurs]] in Xinjiang. In one case ([[Hikvision]]) BlackRock increased its level of investment after the company's blacklisting.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fa-mag.com/news/nonprofit-warns-governors-about-blackrock-retirement-funds--chinese-investments-65225.html |title=Nonprofit Warns Governors About BlackRock Retirement Funds' Chinese Investments |website=fa-mag.com |date=December 3, 2021 |access-date=December 12, 2021}}</ref>

===Ties with Federal Reserve===
BlackRock was scrutinized for allegedly taking advantage of its close ties with the [[Federal Reserve]] during the COVID-19 pandemic response efforts.<ref>Leslie P. Norton. [https://www.barrons.com/articles/blackrock-is-biggest-beneficiary-of-fed-purchases-of-corporate-bond-etfs-51591034726 BlackRock Is Biggest Beneficiary of Fed Purchases of Corporate Bond ETFs], ''Barron's'', June 1, 2020</ref><ref>Richard Henderson and Robin Wigglesworth. [https://www.ft.com/content/08b897a5-aadb-40d7-922c-431154ed968a Fed's big boost for BlackRock raises eyebrows on Wall Street], ''Financial Times'', March 27, 2020</ref><ref>Richard Henderson and Robin Wigglesworth. [https://www.ft.com/content/6a587ebf-064d-48a2-9817-9bc6ccc80591 BlackRock's growing clout carries risks for asset manager: Group faces increased scrutiny as central banks ask it to help run stimulus packages], ''Financial Times'', April 30, 2020</ref> In June 2020, ''[[The New Republic]]'' wrote that BlackRock "was having a very good pandemic" and was casting "itself as socially responsible while contributing to the climate catastrophe, evading regulatory scrutiny, and angling to influence [a potential] [[Presidency of Joe Biden|Biden administration]]."<ref name=vampire/> The ''[[Financial Times]]'' described BlackRock as having secured a prominent advisory role in the Fed’s post-COVID [[Quantitative easing|asset purchase program]], prompting concerns over whether BlackRock would use its influence to encourage the Fed to purchase BlackRock products; during the Fed's 2020 quantitative easing program, BlackRock's corporate bond ETF received $4.3 billion in new investment, compared to the respective $33 million and $15 million received by BlackRock's competitors [[The Vanguard Group|Vanguard Group]] and [[State Street Corporation|State Street]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=2020-05-20 |title=BlackRock trounces ETF rivals after Fed appointment |work=Financial Times |url=https://www.ft.com/content/7091a2a5-7eef-4c78-8331-9fd986925f8a |access-date=2023-02-18}}</ref>

===Involvement in reconstruction of Ukraine===
On December 28, 2022, it was announced that BlackRock and [[Volodymyr Zelensky]] had coordinated a role for the company in the reconstruction of Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/12/28/zelenskyy-blackrock-ceo-fink-agree-to-coordinate-ukraine-investment.html |title=Zelenskyy, BlackRock CEO Fink agree to coordinate Ukraine investment |last=Smith|first=Elliot | work=[[CNBC]] |date=December 28, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221230100238/https://www.cnbc.com/2022/12/28/zelenskyy-blackrock-ceo-fink-agree-to-coordinate-ukraine-investment.html|archive-date=December 30, 2022|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/policy/international/3790699-zelensky-agrees-to-ukraine-rebuild-investment-with-blackrock-ceo/ | title=Zelensky agrees to Ukraine rebuild investment with BlackRock CEO |last=Schonfeld |first=Zach |date=December 28, 2022 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221229172625/https://thehill.com/policy/international/3790699-zelensky-agrees-to-ukraine-rebuild-investment-with-blackrock-ceo/ |archive-date=December 29, 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref> The arrangement was criticized, with BlackRock being accused of "cashing in" on Ukrainian destruction.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Devlin |first=Bradley |title=BlackRock Plots to Buy Ukraine |url=https://www.theamericanconservative.com/blackrock-plots-to-buy-ukraine/ | work=[[The American Conservative]] |date=December 30, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=BlackRock Accused of 'Trying to Cash In On the Disaster' With Ukraine Reconstruction Deal |url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/blackrock-ukraine | first=Brett | last=Wilkins | work=[[Common Dreams]] | date=December 29, 2022}}</ref>

